edu.ucla.sspace.util

Class TreeMultiMap<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.ucla.sspace.util.TreeMultiMap<K,V>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    MultiMap<K,V>, SortedMultiMap<K,V>, Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    BoundedSortedMultiMap

    public class TreeMultiMap<K,V>
extends Object
implements SortedMultiMap<K,V>, Serializable
    A Red-Black tree SortedMultiMap implementation. Map elements are sorted according to the natural ordering of the keys, or by a Comparator provided to the constructor.

    This implementation provides guaranteed log(n) time cost for the containsKey, get, put and remove operations. The remaining operations run in constant time. The only exception is the range method, which runs in constant time except for the first time it is invoked on any sub-map returned by headMap, tailMap, or subMap, when it runs in linear time.

    This map is not thread-safe.

    See Also:
    Map, SortedMap, HashMultiMap, MultiMap, Serialized Form

      • range

        public int range()
        Returns the number of values maped to keys. Note that in the bijective case, this will equal the value returned by MultiMap.size(). However, in the case where a key is mapped to more than one value, this method will always return a value strictly larger than size(). This method runs in constant time, except for the first time called on a sub-map, when it runs in linear time to the number of values.
        Specified by:
        range in interface MultiMap<K,V>
        Returns:
        the number of values maped to keys
